The paper deals with graph algorithms and combinatorial optimization, which are central topics in computer science. The concept of tree spanners is a well-studied topic in graph theory and falls under the category of graph algorithms. The paper also mentions tree-decompositions, which are a fundamental tool in algorithmic graph theory and are studied in the subfield of computational geometry. The paper's focus on bounded tree breadth graphs and their generalizations suggests that it belongs to the subcategories of data structures (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), and graph theory (cs.GT). The paper's use of polynomial time algorithms and its analysis of their running time suggests that it also belongs to the subcategories of discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and social and information networks (cs.SI).
